chunks.html_content:
Business Relief reduces the value of a business or its assets when working out how much Inheritance Tax has to be paid.

Any ownership of a business, or share of a business, is included in the estate for Inheritance Tax purposes.

You can get Business Relief of either 50% or 100% on some of an estate’s business assets, which can be passed on:

  • while the owner is still alive
  • as part of the will

As the executor of the will or administrator of the estate, you can claim Business Relief when you’re valuing the estate.

You should fill in both:

  • form IHT400 (Inheritance Tax account)
  • schedule IHT413 (Business or partnership interests and assets)

You must use the market value of the business or asset when calculating relief at 50%.

You can claim relief on:

  • property and buildings
  • unlisted shares
  • machinery

Business Relief for Inheritance Tax
How to claim relief

You can get Business Relief of either 50% or 100% on some of an estate’s business assets, which can be passed on:

  while the owner is still alive
  as part of the will

As the executor of the will or administrator of the estate, you can claim Business Relief when you’re valuing the estate.
You should fill in both:

  
form IHT400 (Inheritance Tax account)
  
schedule IHT413 (Business or partnership interests and assets)

You must use the market value of the business or asset when calculating relief at 50%.
You can claim relief on:

  property and buildings
  unlisted shares
  machinery

heading_context: What doesn’t qualify for Business Relief
chunks.html_content:
You can get 100% Business Relief on:

  • a business or interest in a business
  • shares in an unlisted company

You can get 50% Business Relief on:

  • shares controlling more than 50% of the voting rights in a listed company
  • land, buildings or machinery owned by the deceased and used in a business they were a partner in or controlled
  • land, buildings or machinery used in the business and held in a trust that it has the right to benefit from

You can only get relief if the deceased owned the business or asset for at least 2 years before they died.

You can’t claim Business Relief if the company:

  • mainly deals with securities, stocks or shares, land or buildings, or in making or holding investments
  • is a not-for-profit organisation
  • is being sold, unless the sale is to a company that will carry on the business and the estate will be paid mainly in shares of that company
  • is being wound up, unless this is part of a process to allow the business of the company to carry on

You can’t claim Business Relief on an asset if it:

  • also qualifies for Agricultural Relief
  • wasn’t used mainly for business in the 2 years before it was either passed on as a gift or as part of the will
  • isn’t needed for future use in the business

If part of a non-qualifying asset is used in the business, that part might qualify for Business Relief.

heading_context: What doesn’t qualify for Business Relief
chunks.html_content: Example If you use one room in a building as a shop and the other rooms are used as your home, the shop will qualify for Business Relief but the rooms won’t.
chunks.plain_content:
Business Relief for Inheritance Tax
What doesn’t qualify for Business Relief
Example
If you use one room in a building as a shop and the other rooms are used as your home, the shop will qualify for Business Relief but the rooms won’t.

chunks.html_content: You may be able to get Business Relief on a transfer of agricultural property (eg farmland, buildings or farm equipment) which isn’t eligible for agricultural relief.
chunks.plain_content:
Business Relief for Inheritance Tax
Relief for agricultural property
You may be able to get Business Relief on a transfer of agricultural property (eg farmland, buildings or farm equipment) which isn’t eligible for agricultural relief.

heading_context: How to get Business Relief on a gift
chunks.html_content:
Someone can give away business property or assets while they’re still alive and the estate can still get Business Relief on Inheritance Tax, as long as the property or assets qualify.

If someone gives away business property or assets, the recipient must keep them as a going concern until the death of the donor if they want to keep the relief.

They can:

  • replace the property or assets - like machinery - with something of equal value if it’s for use in the business
  • only get relief if the donor owned the business or asset for at least 2 years before the date it was given

heading_context: When is a gift no longer liable for Inheritance Tax
chunks.html_content: Any gift made more than 7 years before the donor’s death doesn’t count towards their estate for Inheritance Tax purposes.
chunks.plain_content:
Business Relief for Inheritance Tax
When is a gift no longer liable for Inheritance Tax
Any gift made more than 7 years before the donor’s death doesn’t count towards their estate for Inheritance Tax purposes.

heading_context: When is a gift no longer liable for Inheritance Tax
chunks.html_content: You may have to pay Capital Gains Tax or Income Tax if you sell, give away or exchange (‘dispose of’) an asset or property if it’s gone up in value during the time you owned it.
chunks.plain_content:
Business Relief for Inheritance Tax
When is a gift no longer liable for Inheritance Tax
You may have to pay Capital Gains Tax or Income Tax if you sell, give away or exchange (‘dispose of’) an asset or property if it’s gone up in value during the time you owned it.
